## Output Schema
Return a JSON object with exactly these fields and types:

{
  "components": ["snake_case_name"],
  "material": "<exact material string from the list above>",
  "process": "<exact process string from the list above>",
  "loads": [
    {
      "magnitude_n": <float — total applied force in Newtons>,
      "direction": [<float>, <float>, <float>],
      "location_description": "<where on the part the load is applied>"
    }
  ],
  "boundary_conditions": [
    { "description": "<which faces/edges are fixed and in which DOF>" }
  ],
  "safety_factor": <float — minimum acceptable yield / stress ratio, e.g. 2.0>,
  "tolerance_critical_dims": [
    {
      "nominal_mm": <float>,
      "plus_mm": <float>,
      "minus_mm": <float>,
      "description": "<which feature this dimension controls>"
    }
  ],
  "notes": "<CadQuery-relevant constraints: key dimensions in mm, hole patterns, wall thickness requirements, coordinate system assumptions, mating surface details>"
}

Rules:
- "components" entries must be valid Python identifiers in snake_case (e.g. "base_plate", "cover_lid").
- All numeric values must be JSON floats (e.g. 2.0 not 2).
- If loads or boundary_conditions are not specified, use sensible structural defaults and document them in "notes".
- "notes" is read directly by the CadQuery code generator — include any dimension or geometry detail that constrains the shape.

Output ONLY the JSON object starting with `{`. No explanation, no preamble, no text outside the JSON.
